WEBVTT

00:02.630 --> 00:04.860
See ya! This is an interview. My name is Isabel 
Fernandez, and today's date is the 17th of

00:07.814 --> 00:14.042
November of 1984. I'm going to interview 
Francisco Jose Guerrero from El Salvador, son of

00:14.182 --> 00:27.038
Francisco Jose Guerrero, leader of National 
Conciliation Party, PCN. Today we're going to

00:27.779 --> 00:34.628
discuss US influence on El Salvador elections of 
1984. Now, tell me something about your father.

00:38.528 --> 00:58.101
Well, he, in 1961, when there was military power in 
El Salvador, there were a few military people and

00:38.528 --> 00:58.101
conservative people get together and formed the 
PCN, which was a rough copy of the PRI. from Mexico.

01:00.431 --> 01:08.242
Then, you know, they had a Congress election, and 
PCN took all the seats in the Congress. And my

01:09.223 --> 01:11.746
father got elected president of the Congress. 
That was 1962. But the president was, who was it,

01:13.429 --> 01:16.533
Molina? No, it was Rivera, Coronel Rivera. Then in 
67, it was General... General

01:28.557 --> 01:42.682
Fidel Sanchez Hernandez got elected president 
from the PCN party, and my father was elected

01:28.557 --> 01:42.682
minister of foreign affairs. Oh, okay. In 71, the 
military took

01:45.687 --> 01:53.721
the whole control of the PCN party. which, you 
know, my father didn't like at all, because, you

01:54.005 --> 02:01.073
know, it was a mix-up between conservative people 
and military people. So he resigned. From the PCN.

02:05.337 --> 02:05.998
From the PCN. That was 71. And he got out of the 
politics until 80...

02:14.067 --> 02:15.068
It was 80. The PCN party got thrown out of power by 
some military... in 1979. It was October 15, 1979.

02:27.319 --> 02:29.883
And they were hassled. They were threatened. They 
couldn't have meeting together because the

02:32.526 --> 02:41.899
military junta was to kill that party. They 
decided that they didn't want no PCN to exist. Then

02:47.658 --> 02:55.806
my father and some other conservative people 
started rebuilding the party for the 82 election.

02:56.347 --> 03:00.391
But there was another party formed from the PCN, 
which was ARENA.

03:04.655 --> 03:09.540
In 72, there was Coronel Molina, the president. 
And in 77, it was Coronel Romero, the president.

03:14.140 --> 03:24.657
Both of those people that formed the government, 
that the PCN took from 72 to 79, those were the

03:14.140 --> 03:24.657
people who formed ARENA.

03:27.421 --> 03:33.351
Which, you know, it was more, they were more 
conservative. than the PCN really was. So it was

03:35.963 --> 03:37.565
more right. That's what they call the 
ultra-right. And in 81, my father, he decided to

03:41.489 --> 03:47.416
start rebuilding the PCN, as I was saying. And then 
in 82, we won 14 congressmen out of 60. The

03:58.689 --> 04:02.173
Democratic Party got 24 and Arena got 19. Okay. 
Then my father got elected prime minister for that

04:06.955 --> 04:12.223
because, you know, they divided. It was a Congress 
election in 82. So they all got together to form a

04:15.808 --> 04:22.678
coalition government, all the parties. And my 
father got elected prime minister. In 81. In 82.

04:26.423 --> 04:28.165
Oh, 82. Then he resigned in 82. In 83... And by the 
end of 83, he resigned because he was going to run

04:31.651 --> 04:40.720
for president for the PCN party. In 1984? In 1984. 
And today he's... Today, you know, he got elected

04:45.405 --> 04:51.471
president of the Supreme Court, which is an 
election. He doesn't form, he doesn't, he's a part

04:51.491 --> 04:57.878
for the Duarte's government. Because he's 
elected from the Congress, which Duarte doesn't

04:58.111 --> 05:04.080
have the majority. So, you know, he's like the head 
of the opposition in El Salvador. Okay. And you

05:09.328 --> 05:12.753
were helping your father with the campaign of 
1980? Yeah, that's why I left from here. Because he

05:14.896 --> 05:23.950
needed help, you know, like, to trust, to have a lot 
of trust, and talking to... trying to get, you

05:24.622 --> 05:31.592
know, whatever help we could because, you know, 
they didn't think that the PCN could be rebuilt.

05:31.612 --> 05:32.052
Oh, I see. So you were talking to the people? Yeah, I 
was talking to the people, trying to get the

05:35.077 --> 05:41.365
T-shirts, cheaper T-shirts. You know, we got 
about 200,000 plates, you know, with the PCN

05:41.385 --> 05:46.793
symbol. That's, you know, for the peasants, you 
know, some of them. All right. Okay, I'm going to

05:53.134 --> 05:55.798
ask you the first question. What sector of the 
population supported your father, Spartan?

06:01.387 --> 06:01.708
Easy. Let me explain this. Okay. Okay, now 
Salvador, we got most of the peasants. Of the

06:07.437 --> 06:08.179
peasants? But since, you know, these people, 
these people who used to own the big lands... they

06:15.297 --> 06:17.545
formed the other party, which was ARENA. Those 
were the rich people, right? Yeah, the rich

06:20.918 --> 06:21.681
people. And they tried to convince the peasants to 
vote for ARENA, not for PCN. And it got up to a point,

06:27.970 --> 06:31.395
you know, where we were really close. Arena and 
PCN. What about Duarte? Well, he was always, you

06:35.881 --> 06:38.885
know, in the head. Yeah, he was always ahead. So he 
was first, and then your father's party and Arena

06:40.347 --> 06:45.473
were second. Yeah, but, you know, we never got 
together on the second thing because all they want

06:45.493 --> 06:57.910
is... PCN was always the ultra-right party in El 
Salvador. And my father, he worked so hard to make

06:58.210 --> 07:09.342
it look, you know, to make it, to put it, put the 
party in the middle and, you know, leave it right

06:58.210 --> 07:09.342
now to the ultra right. All right. So he wanted to be 
more center. So, you know, he told all his

07:11.484 --> 07:19.553
followers that, you know, they could vote, you 
know, for whoever they want. But there is always,

07:19.974 --> 07:26.160
before, there were always two parties, PCN and 
PDC. And, you know, they're, Most of the followers

07:28.028 --> 07:32.734
were going to vote against PDC, which is Duarte's 
party. Yes, because they've been voting like that

07:33.455 --> 07:36.279
all their lives. I see. So the population that 
supported your father was the peasants, right?

07:42.427 --> 07:47.214
Most of the peasants and a few rich people, very 
few. So can it be said that your father's party was

07:47.234 --> 07:52.020
the military's party? No, no way. It was the old 
military party. The old ones. Yeah, the old ones.

07:57.743 --> 08:01.066
Like, you know, most of them, you know, are out of 
office. You know, they are generals, but, you

08:01.106 --> 08:04.269
know, out of office. So what party did the military 
support, like? Oh, you know, they... Maybe. You

08:11.716 --> 08:16.121
know, some of them went for us, some of them went for 
ARENA, most of them went for ARENA. Oh, so most of

08:16.441 --> 08:24.529
the military were... Yeah, because in El 
Salvador, since there is a war going on, there is a

08:16.441 --> 08:24.529
lot of young military people. And they are more 
into bullets than dialogue. I see. And my father

08:32.401 --> 08:36.406
was always for the dialogue. Okay. But, you know, 
we got help, Duarte got help from the military too.

08:41.453 --> 08:43.676
Oh, you know, the mayor took part in ghetto. Okay. 
Do you see any possibility of the El Salvadorian

08:44.837 --> 08:52.828
army taking over the elections since it happened 
in 1972?

08:55.525 --> 08:59.670
I don't know what happened in 72, but I don't think 
the army got control of that. That's what Duarte

09:00.992 --> 09:04.136
says. Yeah, that's what Duarte says, that he won 
the election. He really won the election, but he

09:07.180 --> 09:10.084
didn't have the majority. It was a mistake. I'm 
glad my father was out of PCN by then, because he won

09:12.928 --> 09:19.356
the election for sure, but he didn't have the 
majority. So how come he can win the election? No,

09:24.869 --> 09:28.973
because you don't need 50% plus one vote. You need 
51%. I see. So that 1% might be 1,000 votes, 10,000

09:31.936 --> 09:37.541
votes, whatever. And then that was, for me, that 
was the mistake. They could have at least give

09:42.125 --> 09:47.790
Duarte the benefit of the doubt that he won. And 
then, you know, going to Congress, which PCN had

09:48.243 --> 09:54.789
the majority, Coronel Molina was going to be 
elected anyway. As president? As president,

09:56.230 --> 09:58.552
because, you know, that's the law in El Salvador. 
If you don't get the majority, you have to go to

09:58.812 --> 10:01.615
Congress. Oh, and Congress decides. Decides who 
wins. So in this election, the Congress decides

10:04.437 --> 10:08.561
for Molina? Yeah, it was on the military people. 
Oh, okay. All right. Did the U.S. aid workers help

10:12.804 --> 10:16.888
your father with the campaign? No. We kind of were 
told that we were the favorites for the American

10:19.107 --> 10:32.725
because Duarte went too far to the left and Daweson 
went too far to the right. As you know, we got him

10:33.386 --> 10:38.312
talking to Ambassador Pickering a few times. He 
said that he'll look at good eyes if my father goes

10:38.993 --> 10:44.179
to the second round. But that's about it. No, they 
help us, you know, and getting reporters and

10:47.288 --> 10:59.446
getting, you know, a bunch of reporters and media 
to my father's rabbit. Did the U.S. aid workers

10:59.466 --> 11:03.131
help Duarte's campaign? The U.S. government 
didn't help Duarte. The AFL-CIO

11:05.795 --> 11:16.030
gave some money to the AFL-CIO corresponding to El 
Salvador. And, you know, they are the new

11:17.815 --> 11:22.881
population of El Salvador. It's like the agrarian 
reform, people who live in the parts where the

11:22.941 --> 11:30.410
agrarian reform were settled. And, you know, 
since most of them are peasants, you know, they go

11:30.430 --> 11:43.045
door by door, door by door trying to convince 
people to vote for Duarte because Duarte doesn't

11:30.430 --> 11:43.045
have a peasant support. He didn't? He didn't have 
none. I mean, he won only in three departments out

11:45.760 --> 11:54.311
of 14, which were, you know, where the big cities 
were. So he won elections in the city? Yeah, he won

11:56.874 --> 12:03.642
the election in the city, but the peasants, you 
know, always go against him because, you know. All

12:04.964 --> 12:05.224
right. Okay, it's been said that if the U.S. 
retires its help from El Salvador, the

12:05.244 --> 12:14.215
Salvadorian army will collapse. Now, it was clear 
that Reagan administration wanted Duarte to win.

12:20.363 --> 12:26.171
I mean, reading the newspaper, I always read that 
they wanted Duarte, not your father. Either

12:26.231 --> 12:29.456
Davison didn't want that one at all. So do you feel 
that these two facts put a lot of pressure on the

12:29.917 --> 12:34.103
election? People voting for Duarte because maybe 
they felt that if Davison won... You know, if you

12:41.954 --> 12:45.880
see the figures, the figures are very close. I 
think they were 50% to 48%, something like that.

12:50.406 --> 12:54.793
And you can see that most of the peasants vote 
against Duarte. They don't vote for Davison. They

12:56.075 --> 12:58.298
vote against Duarte. Yeah, but your father got 
19%. Davison got 30%. 29%. Davison, okay. 29% and

13:05.809 --> 13:08.253
Duarte got like 44%. 43%. 43%, right. So... I mean, 
a lot of people support him. He kept that vote. He

13:15.604 --> 13:20.195
kept, you know, the people that vote for him, you 
know, they vote again. People from Arena and PCN,

13:21.178 --> 13:30.000
they're more used to, since, you know, we were the 
official party for so many years. the peasants

13:30.368 --> 13:39.480
from the PCN were more used to having buses to take 
them to the boating places. And this time, since we

13:40.501 --> 13:49.053
were not an official party, neither Arena was, we 
couldn't put no buses. Oh, I see. So you see, most of

13:49.974 --> 13:53.659
the people who vote, they just vote. No, but if you 
compare the results from the first round and the

13:54.145 --> 14:01.075
second round, you'll see that Duarte kept their 
votes. He didn't win, you know, people from the PCN

14:02.016 --> 14:06.082
or people from other parties. But Arena, he won 
most of the PCN. But they didn't vote for Dawison

14:09.787 --> 14:13.592
because, you know, it was Dawison. They voted 
against Duarte. All right. So you're saying that

14:18.648 --> 14:21.831
the people didn't vote for Duarte? No. Okay, I see. 
During the campaign, did you get any threats from

14:24.374 --> 14:28.237
any side? We got threats from all sides. You see, 
since, you know, we were the middle, which

14:31.661 --> 14:36.566
Duarte's party used to be the middle party. All 
right. But the guerrillas used to be the far left.

14:41.110 --> 14:42.812
But this time, you know, we were in the middle. We 
got threatened by... leftists, by guerrillas, by

14:47.707 --> 14:50.230
right. Really? Yeah, we get, you know, there was 
once, you know, when I had to tell, you know, I had to

14:51.591 --> 15:05.406
really stand, you know, and tell them, man, if 
you're going to use that, if you're going to pull

14:51.591 --> 15:05.406
that gun, you better use it. Because, you know, 
there was this major of this city from Arena, that

15:05.426 --> 15:11.453
he just went to the rally. and says, you know, there 
is no rally in here. And I was the only one

15:14.410 --> 15:21.240
presenting my father's party in there and a group 
that was playing music. Because, you know, we were

15:21.961 --> 15:31.995
the ones that had the always very happy rallies, 
you know, music, pupusas, and everything.

15:32.035 --> 15:33.657
Because, you know, we wanted to feel happy. Most of 
our buddies are young people. All right. And, you

15:37.808 --> 15:43.976
know, this guy just went, you know, and told us he's 
the boss from that town, and I told him. So he didn't

15:44.677 --> 15:47.601
let you speak to the people? We didn't. Oh, okay. 
Because we have security, too. All right. In your

15:53.269 --> 15:58.456
opinion, why didn't the guerrillas show up their 
ballot to the elections? Because they don't have

15:58.916 --> 16:01.380
the support of the people. If they're They're 
burning buses. They're burning things that the

16:05.682 --> 16:10.687
majority of the people use. I got my own car. If they 
burn a bus in El Salvador, I'm not using that bus.

16:18.214 --> 16:20.096
The majority of the people are using it. The 
bridges, they explode. You see, I can take a plane

16:25.261 --> 16:27.924
and fly over. But the passengers, they cannot 
afford it. the majority of the support of the

16:32.348 --> 16:37.435
people they don't like for it. So you think that 
it's because they knew that the people wouldn't

16:37.455 --> 16:44.424
vote for them, so they decided not to show up? I see. 
Did you feel that the elections were a farce made in

16:46.126 --> 16:55.219
USA so that Reagan could call Congress and keep on 
sending military help? No, it wasn't. It wasn't.

16:56.981 --> 16:57.882
You see, he won. He won mainly Because it was about 
time. He's been trying for so long to be a

17:04.433 --> 17:07.778
president. He was the president of the Junta, 
which is not elected. I'm sure that if all the

17:12.986 --> 17:23.481
parties get together, all the opposition 
parties, we can beat Duarte. But we never did that.

17:25.925 --> 17:28.208
That was our promise, to let Duarte go. All right. 
Was the people forced to vote by threats from the

17:31.607 --> 17:36.934
different parties? And did they vote just out of 
fear? No, not really. You see, the people went to

17:41.921 --> 17:43.283
vote. They wanted to vote? They wanted to vote. 
They wanted to elect somebody. So, okay. You know,

17:52.375 --> 17:54.398
there were no force, no matter. Okay, after the 
first election, Duarte and his son were tied,

17:55.137 --> 17:59.825
right? And a runoff was necessary. Did your father 
get any kind of financial help from CIA so that he

18:02.911 --> 18:10.424
couldn't help Duarte, he would help Duarte? We 
couldn't, we didn't, you see, the main problem of

18:11.105 --> 18:18.879
my father's campaign was money-wise. Right. 
Because, you know, he... He paid out of his own

18:20.568 --> 18:27.818
package most of the campaign. If we could have at 
least $436,000, I think that's what they said,

18:29.400 --> 18:42.397
that my father received, and that campaign, I'm 
sure we would end up in second place. No, but I mean

18:42.417 --> 18:43.899
afterwards. Afterwards. So that your father 
wouldn't... No. We got together with the arena

18:47.855 --> 18:50.720
party to talk. And they just went, clearly, we got a 
cake. Let's divide it. Everyone can do whatever

18:58.615 --> 19:02.923
they want, but let's divide it half and half. And my 
father is not like that. See, he's been in the

19:04.886 --> 19:10.757
politics for so long that he told me, I want these 
issues. to be corrected from your party, you know,

19:11.513 --> 19:14.116
I'll give you all. Even they wanted to change that 
was on for my father. I mean, my father for that was

19:18.301 --> 19:19.683
on. And there was a law given around those days that 
my father was going to be able to run for arena. And

19:28.094 --> 19:30.016
he didn't accept. Oh, really? Yeah, he just went 
straight and told them, too much talking, and no,

19:30.837 --> 19:38.747
no, we're not doing nothing. I see. But if you 
compare figures, most of our people, we have

19:39.931 --> 19:56.218
a neutrality.

19:56.975 --> 20:01.099
But at the same time, we're against Duarte's 
party. See, most of our people vote for Arena.

20:03.921 --> 20:04.362
Okay. Davison wanted a military victory over the 
guerrillas. So did your father, right? No, my

20:10.407 --> 20:12.769
father was for the dialogue all the time. He was? 
